The start symbol S has only two binary productions:

1. S → NT26 NT2  
2. S → NT30 NT7  

Hence the first token of any generated string must be produced by the first non-terminal in one of those productions.

A) S → NT30 NT7  
NT30 can yield only one of the terminals {t7, t19, t10, t4, t5, t8} or the binary form NT10 NT31.  
None of these possibilities can give the first token t13 in the string.  
Therefore this branch is impossible.

B) S → NT26 NT2  
NT26 can begin with a terminal in {t9, t6, t23, t12} or with the binary forms NT18 NT9 or NT31 NT23.  
• If NT26 → terminal, it cannot yield t13.  
• If NT26 → NT31 NT23, the first symbol would be produced by NT31, whose only terminal is t8.  
• If NT26 → NT18 NT9, the first symbol comes from NT18. NT18 can give a terminal in {t22, t18} or expand to NT20 NT30 or NT26 NT14. Repeatedly following the left-hand side of every possible expansion (NT18 → NT20 …, NT20 → NT26 …, NT26 → …) shows that the leftmost non-terminal can only cycle through {NT26, NT18, NT20, NT31} and their direct terminals, none of which can ever reach NT11, the sole producer of t13. Consequently, t13 can never appear as the first token under this branch either.

Since neither of the only two possible top-level derivations can yield a first token t13, the given string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The only non-terminal that can produce the terminal symbol ‘t11’ is  

 NT28 → 't11'  

No other non-terminal has a rule yielding ‘t11’.  
The start symbol S can expand only in the following two ways:

1.  S → NT26 NT2  
2.  S → NT30 NT7  

In a derivation, the first terminal of the generated string must come from the leftmost non-terminal of the chosen production (NT26 or NT30).

• NT30 can either produce a terminal directly (t7, t19, t10, t4, t5, t8) or expand to NT10 NT31, where NT10 is terminal-only (t1, t14, t17, t3). Hence NT30 can never yield ‘t11’.

• NT26 can produce terminals (t9, t6, t23, t12) or expand to NT18 NT9 or NT31 NT23.  
 – NT31 produces only ‘t8’.  
 – NT18 produces terminals (t22, t18) or expands to NT20 NT30 or NT26 NT14; none of these paths introduces NT28, and they ultimately lead back to NT26 or to terminals other than ‘t11’.

Consequently, neither NT26 nor NT30 – nor any structure they can derive in leftmost position – is capable of producing ‘t11’. Therefore no derivation from S can begin with ‘t11’, and the given string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The start symbol S has only two productions:

1. S → NT26 NT2  
2. S → NT30 NT7  

Since the last word of the string is t0 and NT2 is never able (directly or through its productions) to yield t0, rule 1 cannot create the given string.  
Thus the only possible start-rule is

 S → NT30 NT7 .

–––– 1. What can NT30 generate? ––––  
NT30 is extremely restricted:

• NT30 → 't7' | 't19' | 't10' | 't4' | 't5' | 't8'   (one word)  
• NT30 → NT10 NT31                            (two words)  

NT10 is a single terminal (t1, t14, t17 or t3) and NT31 is only t8, so the two–word alternative is “(t1|t14|t17|t3) t8”.  
Consequently NT30 can generate either

 • exactly one word, or  
 • exactly two words whose second word is t8.

The given string begins with t8 …, not with any of {t7, t19, t10, t4, t5}.  
Therefore the only possible way to match the prefix with NT30 is to use the
one-word alternative NT30 → 't8'.  Hence

 NT30 must contribute the single word t8 (the first symbol of the string)  
 and NT7 has to generate the remaining 29 words

 t18 t8 t1 t15 t23 t1 t3 t2 t6 t14 t14 t1 t22 t8 t2 t13 t1 t14 t6 t18 t1 t21 t9 t5 t10 t16 t17 t8 t0

–––– 2. What can NT7 generate? ––––  
The CNF rules for NT7 are only

 NT7 → NT6 NT7  
 NT7 → NT23 NT15  
 NT7 → 't16' | 't0' | 't9'

Hence every derivation of NT7 is of the form

 (NT6)^k · (NT23 NT15)        with k ≥ 0,
or it is a single word (t16, t0, t9).

That means:

• The first k words of the substring must each be produced by NT6.  
  NT6 can produce only the terminals
     { t12, t21, t2, t10, t18, t5, t14, t3, t6 }.

• The (k+1)-st word must be produced by NT23.  
  NT23 can produce only
     { t4, t22, t23, t15, t1, t18 }.

Looking at the 29-word substring that NT7 must generate:

word 1  = t18    (allowed for NT6)  
word 2  = t8      t8 is NOT in NT6’s set and NOT in NT23’s set.

So after the very first NT6 word we already meet a symbol (t8) that
neither NT6 nor NT23 can produce, and thus the required pattern
(NT6)^k · NT23 … cannot start.

Therefore the 29-word tail cannot be derived from NT7 at all, which means
S → NT30 NT7 cannot produce the given string.

Since the alternative start rule (S → NT26 NT2) was already excluded,
the grammar is unable to generate the string.

No
